# AGENTS.local.md — Personal Setup Template

Copy this file to `AGENTS.local.md` (gitignored) and fill in your own values.

## Local Directories

- `/path/to/andy.grails` — parent repo (non-submodule changes: docs, E2E tests, scripts)
- `/path/to/andy.grails.backend` — backend submodule, checked out independently
- `/path/to/andy.grails.frontend` — frontend submodule, checked out independently

## GitHub Access

Set the token before starting any session:

```bash
! export GITHUB_TOKEN=<your-token>
```

Never paste the token directly in chat — use `!` prefix so it stays in the terminal session.

Issue URLs by repo:
- Parent: `https://github.com/aistomin/andy.grails/issues/<n>`
- Backend: `https://github.com/aistomin/andy.grails.backend/issues/<n>`
- Frontend: `https://github.com/aistomin/andy.grails.frontend/issues/<n>`

```bash
curl -s -H "Authorization: token $GITHUB_TOKEN" \
  https://api.github.com/repos/aistomin/<repo>/issues/<number>
```

## Terminology

**review** — Full codebase walkthrough of the relevant repo(s). Identify issues (bugs, code smells, missing things, improvements), cross-reference with open GitHub issues, and produce a report structured as:
1. Issues already tracked in GitHub (with issue numbers)
2. Issues found in code that are NOT yet reported — candidate new tickets

Save the report to `.claude/code-review/<date>-full-review.md` in the parent repo.

**review the changes** — Review only what was modified. Run `git diff` (or `git diff master..HEAD` on a feature branch) in the relevant repo(s), inspect the changed code, and produce the same structured report limited to the scope of those changes. Do NOT walk through unrelated code.

## Workflow

1. User provides a GitHub issue number
2. Agent pulls latest master in the parent repo and updates submodules
3. Agent reads the issue from GitHub and grills the user to understand requirements (use `grill-me` skill)
4. Agent and user iterate on a plan — the plan determines which repo(s) are touched
5. Agent creates a feature branch `Issue-<number>` in the relevant repo(s) (e.g. issue #123 → `Issue-123`)
6. User explicitly says "go" — only then does the agent touch any code
7. Agent verifies changes by following the testing instructions in the relevant repo's README (skip if no testing section exists yet)
8. User reviews; agent writes a conventional commit message
9. Agent never commits or pushes — those belong to the user
